  "doc_id": "8797",
  "text": "Aldehydes are the dominant odor compounds in cooked products because of their relatively low odor thresholds, which were probably generated from thermal interactions of lipids and nonvolatile flavor precursors in garlic, eventually becoming part of the overall flavor of fried garlic oil. In previous studies, acetaldehyde was identified as a volatile component of heat-treated garlic [CITATION_1] . However, it was not found at all in our study. Its absence could be explained by different extraction methods and its low concentration in garlic oil.",
  "correct_citation": {
